#compdef mdzk
# =============================================================================
# mdzk — Knut Magnus Aasrud + Victor Freire's "CLI and library
#        for querying connected notes" — a Rust CLI for
#        managing Zettelkasten-style interconnected notes
#        (similar to Obsidian, Roam Research, Logseq, but
#        offline, plain-text, queryable).  Parses Markdown
#        notes with wiki-style `[[Note Name]]` backlinks,
#        builds the bidirectional link graph, and exposes
#        the entire vault as a queryable JSON structure
#        traversable via jql (JSON Query Language).
#        Distinguishing from Obsidian (proprietary GUI),
#        Logseq (Electron app), zk (zk-org/zk), Roam Research
#        (web SaaS), and other connected-notes tools by:
#          - PLAIN-TEXT MARKDOWN STORAGE — no database, no
#            proprietary format; just `.md` files in a
#            directory; works with any editor, git, grep
#          - PARSING NOTES INTO A QUERYABLE GRAPH — mdzk
#            walks the source dir, parses each Markdown file
#            via pulldown-cmark, extracts `[[wiki-style]]`
#            backlinks, identifies `front-matter` metadata
#            (YAML/TOML), and constructs a vault JSON object
#            with notes + links + backlinks + tags
#          - JQL QUERY LANGUAGE — mdzk uses jql (JSON Query
#            Language) for traversing the vault:
#              mdzk '"notes"|>"my-note"|>"backlinks"'
#              mdzk '"notes"|.[]|>"tags"'  # all tags
#          - SHELL-COMPATIBLE OUTPUT via -r/--raw — emits
#            results as bare strings + arrays suitable for
#            shell pipelines:
#              mdzk -r '"notes"|.[]|>"title"' | xargs -I{}
#              ...
#          - PRETTY JSON via --pretty — for human inspection
#          - GITIGNORE-COMPATIBLE EXCLUSION via -i/--ignore
#            (multiple) — same syntax as .gitignore
#          - 5-LEVEL LOGGING via -l/--log-level (default 3)
#            — error (1) / warn (2) / info (3) / debug (4) /
#            trace (5)
#          - VAULT MODEL — `mdzk::VaultBuilder` is the public
#            Rust API; the CLI is a thin wrapper exposing the
#            vault as JSON
#          - FRONT-MATTER PARSING via gray_matter — YAML / TOML
#            / JSON front-matter blocks parsed into note
#            metadata
#          - BIDIRECTIONAL LINKS — every `[[backlink]]` in
#            file A pointing to file B generates BOTH:
#              - links[]: A → B
#              - backlinks[]: B ← A
#          - FNV HASHING via fnv crate — fast content hashing
#            for change detection
#        Used by: Zettelkasten + knowledge-management
#        practitioners wanting a plain-text + queryable
#        alternative to Obsidian / Roam, researchers building
#        custom note-graph analyses, and as a reference
#        implementation of pulldown-cmark + jql + gray_matter
#        + clap derive composition in Rust.
#
# Author:  Knut Magnus Aasrud (km@aasrud.com) + Victor Freire
#          (victor@freire.dev.br).  Norwegian / Brazilian Rust
#          developers.  mdzk released ~2021; current version
#          1.0.0; active development through 2026.  License:
#          custom permissive (see LICENSE file).
# Source:  https://github.com/mdzk-rs/mdzk
#          https://github.com/mdzk-rs/mdzk/blob/main/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/mdzk-rs/mdzk/blob/main/Cargo.toml
#          https://mdzk.app
# CLI:     src/main.rs — uses clap v4 derive (well-documented
#          elsewhere).  Headline library: **pulldown-cmark**
#          (clap is documented across hundreds of Rust
#          completions; pulldown-cmark is the new variant
#          being documented here, opening Axis 19 — Markdown
#          Parsing).
# Library: pulldown-cmark (https://github.com/pulldown-cmark/
#          pulldown-cmark — "An efficient, reliable parser for
#          CommonMark, a standard dialect of Markdown" —
#          original author Raph Levien (Google Fonts, Skia,
#          Inkscape, Druid contributor); currently maintained
#          by a community team under the pulldown-cmark org.
#          Distinct from all previously-documented Rust libraries
#          by being:
#             1. COMMONMARK 0.31 COMPLIANT — pulldown-cmark
#                passes the full CommonMark 0.31 spec test
#                suite (>650 tests).  Distinct from
#                markdown-rs (cmark-gfm-port), from comrak
#                (GitHub-Flavored Markdown), and from
#                markdown crate (pure-Rust but smaller).
#             2. EVENT-BASED PULL PARSER — pulldown-cmark
#                emits `Event` enum values as an Iterator:
#                  use pulldown_cmark::{Parser, Event};
#                  let md = "# Hello\nWorld";
#                  let parser = Parser::new(md);
#                  for event in parser {
#                    match event {
#                      Event::Start(tag) => { /* heading, paragraph, etc. */ }
#                      Event::End(tag)   => { }
#                      Event::Text(s)    => { /* "Hello", "World" */ }
#                      Event::Code(s)    => { }
#                      Event::Html(s)    => { }
#                      Event::FootnoteReference(name) => { }
#                      _ => {}
#                    }
#                  }
#                Pull-parsing minimizes memory: never allocates
#                full AST; events stream as the parser
#                advances.  Distinct from comrak (full DOM
#                tree) and from markdown crate (similar pull
#                but different API).
#             3. EFFICIENT — pulldown-cmark benchmarks ~200x
#                faster than markdown.js per byte; among the
#                fastest CommonMark implementations across
#                all languages.  Pull-parsing + zero-copy
#                string handling.
#             4. OPTIONAL GFM EXTENSIONS — `Options` flags
#                enable GitHub-Flavored Markdown features:
#                  Options::ENABLE_TABLES
#                  Options::ENABLE_FOOTNOTES
#                  Options::ENABLE_STRIKETHROUGH
#                  Options::ENABLE_TASKLISTS
#                  Options::ENABLE_HEADING_ATTRIBUTES
#                  Options::ENABLE_SMART_PUNCTUATION
#                Distinct from comrak (always-on GFM).
#             5. HTML RENDERER — `pulldown_cmark::html::push_html`
#                + `write_html` render events to an output
#                string / Write impl:
#                  use pulldown_cmark::{Parser, html, Options};
#                  let mut output = String::new();
#                  let parser = Parser::new_ext(md, Options::all());
#                  html::push_html(&mut output, parser);
#             6. ZERO-COPY where possible — events borrow from
#                input string lifetime; reduces allocations.
#             7. INVERSE-LINK SUPPORT via separate
#                pulldown-cmark-to-cmark crate for round-
#                tripping CommonMark → events → CommonMark.
#             8. RAPH-LEVIEN PROVENANCE — Raph Levien is a
#                long-time graphics + fonts engineer at
#                Google; previously contributed to Inkscape,
#                Skia, FreeType, and now Druid (Rust UI
#                framework).  pulldown-cmark was Raph's 2017
#                project; community-maintained since 2021.
#             9. USED BY mdbook — Steve Klabnik + Rust team's
#                mdbook (the Rust Book, the Cargo Book, the
#                Rustonomicon, the Reference) uses
#                pulldown-cmark.  Foundational dependency of
#                the Rust documentation ecosystem.
#            10. PULLDOWN-CMARK-RS / COMMUNITY-MAINTAINED —
#                originally raphlinus/pulldown-cmark; moved
#                to the pulldown-cmark org in 2021 for
#                community maintenance.
# License: MIT (pulldown-cmark); custom permissive (mdzk)
# Status:  pulldown-cmark — 2,581+ stars on pulldown-cmark/
#          pulldown-cmark, ~120M crates.io downloads (TOP-100
#          Rust crate); foundational Markdown library used by:
#            * mdbook (Rust documentation books)
#            * mdbook-* preprocessors (mermaid, linkcheck, etc.)
#            * cargo docs (Markdown rendering in some flows)
#            * Zola (static site generator)
#            * Cobalt (static site generator)
#            * Blades (static site generator)
#            * Hugo-rs (Rust Hugo alternative)
#            * Pulldown-cmark integrations in 1500+ Rust
#              applications
#          mdzk — 248+ stars on mdzk-rs/mdzk, used by
#          Zettelkasten + knowledge-management practitioners.
#
